ents with aggressive B-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma treated with reduced-dose chemotherapy. Int J Clin Oncol. 2016;21(3):498&#x2013;505. 10.1007/s10147-015-0912-6.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1007/s10147-015-0912-6</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">26463529</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Hernandez-Ilizaliturri FJ, Deeb G, Zinzani PL, et al. Higher response to lenalidomide in relapsed/refractory diffuse large B-cell lymphoma in nongerminal center B-cell-like than in germinal center B-cell-like phenotype. Cancer. 2011;117(22):5058&#x2013;66. 10.1002/cncr.26135.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1002/cncr.26135</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">21495023</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Nowakowski GS, Chiappella A, Gascoyne RD, et al. ROBUST: a phase III study of lenalidomide plus R-CHOP versus placebo plus R-CHOP in previously untreated patients with ABC-type diffuse large B-cell lymphoma. J Clin Oncol. 2021;39(12):1317&#x2013;28. 10.1200/JCO.20.01366.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1200/JCO.20.01366</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC8078325</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">33621109</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41922143</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>22</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>20</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2059-7029</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>11</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>ESMO open</Title><ISOAbbreviation>ESMO Open</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Comparative efficacy of zanubrutinib plus obinutuzumab versus last prior treatment in relapsed/refractory follicular lymphoma: growth modulation index analysis from the ROSEWOOD study.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>106942</StartPage><MedlinePgn>106942</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">106942</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.esmoop.2026.106942</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S2059-7029(26)00884-7</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">The phase II ROSEWOOD study (NCT03332017) compared zanubrutinib plus obinutuzumab (ZO) with obinutuzumab monotherapy (O) in patients with relapsed/refractory (R/R) follicular lymphoma (FL) who had received two or more prior lines of systemic therapy. Median progression-free survival (PFS) was longer with ZO versus O [28.0 versus 10.4 months; hazard ratio 0.50, 95% confidence interval (CI) 0.33-0.75].</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="MATERIALS AND METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">In this post hoc analysis, an intra-patient comparative analysis was carried out using the growth modulation index (GMI) to analyze the efficacy of ZO versus the last prior treatment received by patients in the ROSEWOOD study. A GMI of &#x2265;1.33 was used as a threshold for significant clinical activity.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">In the overall population, median GMI was 2.7 (95% CI 1.6-4.9) in the ZO arm and 0.9 (95% CI 0.5-1.7) in the O arm. Analysis in subgroups of clinical interest in the ZO arm showed that PFS was longer with ZO than with the last prior treatment, and median GMI was &#x2265;1.33 in all subgroups tested. Overall, PFS had improved (GMI &#x2265;1.33) in &gt;60% of patients with R/R FL who received ZO versus their last prior treatment.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">This GMI analysis further supports the benefit of ZO as a novel therapeutic option for patients with R/R FL.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 The Authors. Published by Elsevier Ltd.. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Trotman</LastName><ForeName>J</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Hematology, Concord Repatriation General Hospital, University of Sydney, Concord, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bouabdallah</LastName><ForeName>K</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>H&#xf4;pital Haut-L&#xe9;v&#xea;que, CHU Bordeaux, Pessac, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bijou</LastName><ForeName>F</ForeName><Initials>F</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institut Bergoni&#xe9;, Bordeaux, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>&#x160;&#xe1;lek</LastName><ForeName>D</ForeName><Initials>D</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Internal Medicine, Hematology and Oncology, University Hospital Brno and Masaryk University, Brno, Czech Republic.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>de Oliveira</LastName><ForeName>A C</ForeName><Initials>AC</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institut Catala d'Oncologia (ICO) Hospital Duran I Reynals, Barcelona, Spain.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Song</LastName><ForeName>Y</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Peking University Cancer Hospital and Institute, Beijing, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kingsley</LastName><ForeName>E C</ForeName><Initials>EC</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Comprehensive Cancer Centers of Nevada, Las Vegas, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Flowers</LastName><ForeName>C R</ForeName><Initials>CR</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Lymphoma/Myeloma, University of Tex